<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="554" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1437,152,647]" pageId="9" pageNumber="554">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,396,440,467]" pageId="9" pageNumber="554">Biological notes.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Emery" authorityYear="1920" box="[405,623,441,467]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Camponotus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="554" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ionius">
<emphasis box="[405,623,441,467]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="554">Camponotus ionius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a common species, known from various 
<typeStatus box="[1126,1185,441,467]" pageId="9" pageNumber="554">types</typeStatus>
of arid habitats, most commonly noted from pine forests, but also observed in olive plantations, deciduous forests, and gardens in urban areas. Workers are also occasionally observed in open habitats, especially pastures with xerothermous shrubs and limestone rocks or large stones. Nests can be found under large stones. Workers are active usually at dawn and dusk. Major workers forage up to 10 meters away from the nest and are often collected on roads or tree trunks. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Emery" authorityYear="1920" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Camponotus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="554" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ionius">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="554">Camponotus ionius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is also one of the pioneer species in burned forests.
</paragraph>
